quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to set the letter spacing of the paragraph:
[!raw!]
p { 
   {0}-{1}: 4px; 
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The letter-spacing Property[/h1]

The letter-spacing property specifies the [b]space between characters[/b] in a text. The values can be set as:
- [b]normal[/b] defines the default style with no extra space between characters
- [b]length[/b] defines an extra space between characters using measurement units like px, pt, cm, mm, etc.;
- [b]inherit[/b] inherits the property from its parent element;

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="normal">This paragraph has no additional letter-spacing applied.</p>
<p class="positive ">This paragraph is letter-spaced at 4px.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="531"]p.normal { 
   [b]letter-spacing: normal;[/b] 
}
p.positive { 
   [b]letter-spacing: 4px; [/b]
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2607" width="100%"]

[h1]Using Negative Values[/h1]

For defining an extra space between characters, negative values are also permitted. 
Here is an example demonstrating the difference between [b]positive[/b] and [b]negative[/b] values: 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="positive">This paragraph is letter-spaced at 4px.</p>
<p class="negative">This paragraph is letter-spaced at -1.5px</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="532"]p.positive { 
   letter-spacing: 4px; 
}
p.negative { 
   letter-spacing: -1.5px; 
} [/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2608" width="100%"]
[note]Always test your result, to ensure the text is readable.[/note]
